      <div class="seo-concept-faq-list reveal">
        <details class="seo-concept-faq-item" open>
          <summary>How much traffic do we need to start CRO?</summary>
          <p>While some audits can be done immediately, for statistically significant A/B testing, we typically look for at least 10k monthly visitors or 500 conversions to ensure fast results.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item seo-concept-faq-item">
          <summary>What is the 'Scientific Method' in CRO?</summary>
          <p>It means we don't guess. We observe data -> create a hypothesis -> build an experiment -> analyze results. If the data shows the new version is better, we deploy it.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item seo-concept-faq-item">
          <summary>What is the difference between A/B testing and multivariate testing?</summary>
          <p>A/B testing compares two versions of a whole page or element. Multivariate testing tests several elements at once to see which combination performs best for your goal.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item seo-concept-faq-item">
          <summary>How long does a typical A/B test take?</summary>
          <p>Depending on your traffic, a test typically runs for 2-4 weeks. We need enough data to reach at least a 95% confidence level before calling a winner.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item seo-concept-faq-item">
          <summary>Do we need to change our website to do CRO?</summary>
          <p>We use testing tools like VWO or Optimizely that can run experiments without changing your core code initially. Once we find a winner, we then implement it permanently.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="faq-item seo-concept-faq-item">
          <summary>How do you measure the ROI of CRO?</summary>
          <p>We look at Revenue per Visitor (RPV), Conversion Rate (%), and Order Value. Our goal is to make every dollar of your current ad spend more profitable through better efficiency.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
